{{Infobox Film Festival | name = Alchemy Film & Moving Image Festival | image = Alchemy Film & Moving Image Festival at Heart of Hawick.png | caption = The audience awaits a film screening at the 2018 festival | location = [[Hawick]], [[Scotland]] | language = English | founded = 2009 | website = http://www.alchemyfilmfestival.org.uk }}
'''Alchemy Film & Moving Image Festival''' is an annual [[film festival]] held in [[Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theskinny.co.uk/festivals/uk-festivals/film/alchemy-film-and-moving-image-festival-2018 |title=Alchemy Film & Moving Image Festival: 2018 Report |last=Dunn |first=Jamie |publisher=The Skinny |date=May 15, 2018 |access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> It is considered a leading festival of experimental and artists' film within the UK and Europe.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cloughton |first=Rachael |date=2016 |title=Alchemy Film Festival |url=https://alchemyfilmfestival.org.uk/wp/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Scottish-Art-News-Autumn-2016.pdf |magazine=Scottish Art News |location=Scotland |publisher=Fleming-Wyfold Art Foundation |access-date=October 1, 2016}}</ref> The first edition was held in September 2010<ref>{{cite web |url=https://alchemyfilmfestival.org.uk/2010/programme.pdf |title=Alchemy Film & Moving Image Festival 2010 Programme |publisher=Alchemy Film & Arts |date=September 2010 |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref> and the festival shows around 130 films each year, with a mixed programme of short films, feature films, moving image installations, specialist curated programmes and live expanded cinema performances.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://film.list.co.uk/article/100156-alchemy-film-and-moving-image-festival-launches-its-2018-programme/ |title=Alchemy Film and Moving Image Festival 2018 |last=Robertson |first=Murray |publisher=The List |date=April 11, 2018 |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/film/film-review-alchemy-film-and-moving-image-festival-1-4382673 |title=Film review: Alchemy Film and Moving Image Festival|last=Harkness |first=Alistair |publisher=The Scotsman |date=March 4, 2017 |access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>
Situated in the rural [[Scottish Borders]] town of [[Hawick]] the festival's Creative Director, [[Richard Ashrowan]], described its foundation as "a provocation to the prevailing urban-centrism in terms of culture".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.creativescotland.com/explore/read/stories/film/2017/filmmakers-and-artists-head-to-hawick-for-alchemy-film-and-moving-image-festival |title=Filmmakers and artists head to Hawick for Alchemy Film Festival |publisher=Creative Scotland |date=February 20, 2016 |access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref> The main cinema screenings are held in an award-winning converted spinning mill, Tower Mill, which is part of Heart of [[Hawick]], a key partner organisation for the festival. The festival also utilises a variety of disused and ex-industrial spaces for moving image installations throughout the town.
Alchemy has premiered screenings by such filmmakers as [[Jan Švankmajer]], [[Sarah Pucill]], [[Andrew Kötting]], [[Rachel Maclean]], [[The Quay Brothers]], [[Semiconductor (artists)]], [[Mike Hoolboom]], [[Nina Danino]], [[Patrick Bokanowski]], [[Jacques Perconte]], [[Mark Leckey]], and [[Ben Rivers]].
Alchemy Film & Moving Image Festival is run by Alchemy Film & Arts, which is registered with the [[Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator]]. It develops projects for [[experimental film]] and artists’ moving image production in Scotland. These include artists’ filmmaking residencies, exhibitions programmes, filmmaking symposia, touring programmes and community film projects. In 2017, Alchemy Film & Arts curated Scotland’s national exhibition at the [[Venice Biennale]], presenting a film commission by the artist filmmaker [[Rachel Maclean]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/art/interview-rachel-maclean-on-representing-scotland-at-the-venice-biennale-1-4436314 |title=Interview: Rachel Maclean on representing Scotland at the Venice Biennale |last=Mansfield |first=Susan |publisher=The Scotsman |date=May 9, 2017 |access-date=May 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/52GWHmvrCNGKGRMQjT0kcFP/rachel-maclean-a-grotesque-disney-for-the-facebook-generation |title=Rachel Maclean: A grotesque Disney for the Facebook generation |last=Cook |first=William |publisher=BBC |date=May 9, 2017 |access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/art/art-reviews-rachel-maclean-david-claerbout-marcelo-brodsky-calum-mcclure-1-4709677 |title=Art reviews: Rachel Maclean|last=Mansfield |first=Susan |publisher=The Scotsman |date=March 21, 2018 |access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>
